SIMPLE: peep
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Peep
<hw>Peep</hw> <pr>(p⟦emac⟧p)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Peeped</conjf> <pr>(p⟦emac⟧pt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Peeping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Of imitative
origin; cf. OE. <ets>pipen</ets>, F. <ets>piper</ets>,
<ets>p⟦eacute⟧pier</ets>, L. <ets>pipire</ets>, <ets>pipare</ets>,
<ets>pipiare</ets>, D. & G. <ets>piepen</ets>. Senses 2 and 3 perhaps
come from a transfer of sense from the sound which chickens make upon
the first breaking of the shell to the act accompanying it; or perhaps
from the influence of <ets>peek</ets>, or <ets>peak</ets>. Cf.
<er>Pipe</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cry, as a chicken hatching or
newly hatched; to chirp; to cheep.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was none that moved the wing, or opened the mouth, or
<qex>peeped</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Is. x. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To begin to appear; to look forth from concealment;
to make the first appearance; <as>as, the sun <ex>peeped</ex> over the
eastern hills</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When flowers first <qex>peeped</qex>, and trees did blossoms
bear.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1058 --></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To look cautiously or slyly; to peer, as through a
crevice; to pry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Peep</qex> through the blanket of the dark.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From her cabined loophole <qex>peep</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Peep sight</b></col>, <cd>an adjustable piece, pierced
with a small hole to peep through in aiming, attached to a rifle or
other firearm near the breech.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peep</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Peep
<hw>Peep</hw> <pr>(p⟦emac⟧p)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
cry of a young chicken; a chirp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>First outlook or appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Oft have we seen him at the <qex>peep</qex> of dawn.</q>
<rj><qau>Gray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A sly look; a look as through a crevice, or from a
place of concealment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To take t' other <qex>peep</qex> at the stars.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any small sandpiper,
as the least sandpiper (<spn>Trigna minutilla</spn>).</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>The European meadow pipit (<spn>Anthus pratensis</spn>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Peep show</b></col>, <cd>a small show, or object
exhibited, which is viewed through an orifice or a magnifying
glass.</cd> -- <col><b>Peep-o'-day boys</b></col>, <cd>the Irish
insurgents of 1784; -- so called from their visiting the house of the
loyal Irish at day break in search of arms.</cd>
<mark>[Cant]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peeper</ent>⟦br⟧
